{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14131"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14131"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0,0.11,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1021"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15394"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with dizziness and fatigue. Her parent, who accompanies her, is worried about her recent significant weight loss. The patient believes she is \u0027overweight\u0027 despite losing 18 kg over the past eight months. She admits to following a strict plant-based diet, avoiding all fats and carbohydrates, and exercising vigorously for 90 minutes every morning before eating. She has not menstruated for five months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn further questioning, the patient reports feeling anxious and low in mood. She describes intrusive thoughts about food contamination and spends considerable time each day examining her body in the mirror. She also mentions occasional episodes of feeling out of control and consuming large amounts of food, followed by feelings of guilt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears severely underweight. Her pulse rate is 48/min, blood pressure 85/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. Her BMI is calculated as 16.8 kg/m2. There is fine, downy hair visible on her face and arms, and her skin is dry with poor elasticity. Mild swelling of the extremities is noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obsessive-compulsive disorder","Bulimia nervosa","Major depressive disorder","Body dysmorphic disorder","Anorexia nervosa"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eanorexia nervosa\u003C/strong\u003E. Key features supporting this diagnosis include significant weight loss, restrictive eating patterns, excessive exercise, distorted body image, and physiological changes such as amenorrhoea, bradycardia, hypotension, lanugo-like body hair, and peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E can involve weight changes and reduced appetite. While the patient reports low mood, her intense fear of weight gain and body image disturbance are more characteristic of anorexia nervosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBulimia nervosa\u003C/strong\u003E involves recurrent episodes of binge eating followed by compensatory behaviours. Although this patient exercises excessively and mentions occasional uncontrolled eating, her predominant pattern of food restriction and significant weight loss aligns more closely with anorexia nervosa. Individuals with bulimia are normal or overweight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObsessive-compulsive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (OCD) may involve rituals around food and eating, and the patient\u0027s intrusive thoughts about food contamination suggest OCD features. However, the severe weight loss and body image disturbance are more indicative of anorexia nervosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody dysmorphic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves preoccupation with perceived physical flaws, which is suggested by the patient\u0027s mirror-checking behaviour. However, it typically doesn\u0027t involve the restrictive eating and weight loss seen in anorexia nervosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe DSM-5 diagnostic criteria for anorexia nervosa include: significantly restricted energy intake leading to low body weight, intense fear of weight gain, and disturbed experience of one\u0027s body weight or shape. A BMI below 18.5 kg/m2 is considered underweight in adults. Amenorrhoea, while present in this case, is no longer a required criterion for diagnosis. This patient\u0027s presentation meets all these criteria, making anorexia nervosa the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anorexia nervosa is characterised by restricted food intake, intense fear of weight gain, and distorted body image perception.","In adults, a BMI below 18.5 kg/m2 is considered underweight and may indicate anorexia nervosa if other diagnostic criteria are met.","Amenorrhoea is no longer required for diagnosing anorexia nervosa according to DSM-5 criteria."],"references":["Hodo DW. Kaplan and Sadock\u2019s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. American Journal of Psychiatry. 2006 Aug;163(8):1458-.","Hay P, Chinn D, Forbes D, Madden S, Newton R, Sugenor L, Touyz S, Ward W. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the treatment of eating disorders. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2014 Nov;48(11):977-1008. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25351912/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14131"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T11:10:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T11:11:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6811"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"